        <Parent_String>marbled paper [300265095], paper by production method [300157807], paper (fiber product) [300014109], fiber by product [300014062], fiber and fiber by product [300014023], materials by physical form [300247256], materials by form [300014611], materials (substances) [300010358], Materials (hierarchy name) [300010357], Materials Facet [300264091]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Paper having a German pattern that is not true marbling, but was very popular in the 19th century and was classified as a marbled paper. It is characterized by heavy, small, dark spots with a darker outer rim on a bright-colored background.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000050840/Easton, Marbling (1983)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>一種具有德國紋理的紙張，並非真正的大理石花紋，但是在西元十九世紀時非常受到歡迎，因此被歸類為一種大理石花紋紙。它的特徵在於厚重、微小、深暗的點狀圖案，在色澤明亮的背景中，有著一道顏色更暗的外圍邊框。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
